				\begin{document}$$\mathbf{z}$$\end{document}z is the vertical axis of the global coordinate system. From a mechanical point of view, the CoM height should be defined as from the center of pressure (CoP) to the CoM. Because the gibbon’s foot contacts with the side of the pole substrate in the pole condition (Fig. 2a), the CoP should be below the top of the pole. As the height of the CoP decreases, the height of the ankle joint also decreases, such that the vertical distance from the right LM to the CoM was defined as the CoM height in this study.

